- Sergeant Park.

487
00:40:13,477 --> 00:40:16,547
(speaking in foreign language)

488
00:40:16,547 --> 00:40:17,882
- Ask her who she is.

489
00:40:17,882 --> 00:40:19,984
- That's all right, I speak English.

490
00:40:19,984 --> 00:40:21,585
I'm Waranya.

491
00:40:21,585 --> 00:40:23,087
- Waranya?

492
00:40:23,087 --> 00:40:23,921
- Yes.

493
00:40:25,122 --> 00:40:26,657
Have your men rest in our huts.

494
00:40:27,725 --> 00:40:29,226
- Okay, thank you.

495
00:40:33,697 --> 00:40:36,100
- We don't see Americans here often.

496
00:40:36,100 --> 00:40:37,968
What are you doing here, are you lost?

497
00:40:39,503 --> 00:40:41,305
- Yeah, you might say that.

498
00:40:41,305 --> 00:40:43,908
We got in a firefight with some NVA regulars.

499
00:40:43,908 --> 00:40:45,843
Got a bit sidetracked.

500
00:40:45,843 --> 00:40:47,411
- We don't have much to offer,

501
00:40:47,411 --> 00:40:49,547
but we'll do what we can for you and your men.

502
00:40:49,547 --> 00:40:50,514
- I appreciate that.

503
00:40:53,651 --> 00:40:56,720
- What do we do now, Troop, go back to Tay Ninh or what?

504
00:40:59,390 --> 00:41:01,292
- Well, the next contact's at zero hour.

505
00:41:03,360 --> 00:41:04,929
We'll see what the colonel thinks then.

506
00:41:06,997 --> 00:41:09,300
In the meantime, the NVA knows we're out here.

507
00:41:11,502 --> 00:41:13,037
(groaning)

508
00:41:13,037 --> 00:41:15,406
- It's a fucking hardball world, ladies.

509
00:41:17,641 --> 00:41:19,176
- We better set up for the night.

510
00:41:19,176 --> 00:41:23,180
Ski, take ASP, set up a defensive perimeter

511
00:41:23,180 --> 00:41:25,282
at the edge of the village.

512
00:41:25,282 --> 00:41:26,383
I'll come out and relieve you at--

513
00:41:26,383 --> 00:41:28,285
- That's not necessary, captain.

514
00:41:28,285 --> 00:41:30,254
We've got our own eyes in the jungle.

515
00:41:30,254 --> 00:41:32,523
And believe me, we'll have an ample warning

516
00:41:32,523 --> 00:41:34,158
about any unwelcome guests.

517
00:41:37,561 --> 00:41:40,231
(ominous tones)

518
00:42:12,029 --> 00:42:13,364
- Husband?

519
00:42:13,364 --> 00:42:14,865
- My brother.

520
00:42:14,865 --> 00:42:15,699
This is for you.

521
00:42:18,869 --> 00:42:19,870
- Thank you.

522
00:42:24,942 --> 00:42:26,076
- Bitter?

523
00:42:26,076 --> 00:42:26,911
- No, no.

524
00:42:30,347 --> 00:42:31,582
Maybe a little.

525
00:42:32,816 --> 00:42:34,952
Where did you learn to speak English?

526
00:42:34,952 --> 00:42:36,220
- From the nuns.

527
00:42:36,220 --> 00:42:37,321
I speak French too.

528
00:42:40,257 --> 00:42:43,761
- This is beautiful country around here.

529
00:42:43,761 --> 00:42:46,697
It's very quiet and serene.

530
00:42:50,334 --> 00:42:53,070
But your people, they seem so hostile.

531
00:42:54,538 --> 00:42:56,874
- We are a peaceful people,

532
00:42:56,874 --> 00:42:59,009
but we want the NVA out of our country.

533
00:43:00,210 --> 00:43:02,413
Our own government won't even help us.

534
00:43:02,413 --> 00:43:04,748
So we do what little we can when we can

535
00:43:05,683 --> 00:43:07,685
with our own limited resources.

536
00:43:09,420 --> 00:43:11,855
- Do you realize what would happen if you got caught?

537
00:43:13,524 --> 00:43:15,593
- If they knew what we were up to,

538
00:43:15,593 --> 00:43:17,428
they're gonna wipe us out any minute.

539
00:43:18,829 --> 00:43:23,434
I suppose that makes us very brave or very foolish.

540
00:43:25,102 --> 00:43:26,170
- Well, there's nothing foolish

541
00:43:26,170 --> 00:43:27,771
about fighting for your country.

542
00:43:29,306 --> 00:43:30,975
- My father would have disagreed.

